{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516017"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12546"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.42,0.21,0.02,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77732"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5045"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63248"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"426"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"8908"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77732"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man is referred to his ophthalmologist with sudden onset of painless vision loss in his left eye over the past 1 week which has neither improved nor worsened. He had noticed this change after getting up one morning. He has no headaches, fever, or weight loss. He has a past medical history of hypertension and diabetes for which he takes perindopril and metformin. On examination, there is no anisocoria and he has a relative afferent pupillary defect in the left eye with an inferior visual field defect. Fundoscopy reveals optic disc swelling with splinter hemorrhages and cotton wool spots.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral corticosteroids","Fluorescein angiography","Orbital MRI","Lumbar puncture","Referral to a neurologist"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of painless vision loss in one eye with a relative afferent pupillary defect and optic disc swelling with splinter hemorrhages and cotton wool spots is suggestive of non-arteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy (NAION). NAION is a potentially debilitating condition that occurs from a lack of sufficient blood flow to the optic nerve. It is a clinical diagnosis, and the most appropriate next step in management is to order a \u003Cstrong\u003Efluorescein angiography\u003C/strong\u003E to rule out other causes of optic disc swelling such as posterior ischemic optic neuropathy or papilloedema. Vascular risk factors should be optimised. There are currently no treatments for NAION that are proven to be effective. Further prospective studies will need to be carried out to determine role of corticosteroids. About 25% of patients with NAION get some visual recovery whilst there is a 25% risk of a similar event to the other eye (particularly if the optic disc is small: \u0022disc at risk\u0022).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended as they have not been shown to improve visual outcomes in NAION. If symptoms suggesting giant cell arteritis are present such as headache, jaw pain, and scalp tenderness, corticosteroids should be administered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn orbital MRI\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary unless there is a concern for an alternative diagnosis such as cerebral venous sinus thrombosis or if the fluorescein angiography is inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA lumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in some cases to rule out underlying causes of NAION such as giant cell arteritis, but it is not the most appropriate next step in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to a neurologist\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate if there are other neurological symptoms or if the diagnosis is unclear, but it is not the most appropriate next step in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["NAION is a clinical diagnosis and treatment is typically supportive.","Fluorescein angiography is used to differentiate between various causes of optic disc swelling."],"references":["Saxena R, Singh D, Sharma M, James M, Sharma P, Menon V. Steroids versus No Steroids in Nonarteritic Anterior Ischemic Optic Neuropathy: A Randomized Controlled Trial. Ophthalmology. 2018 Oct;125(10):1623-1627. doi: 10.1016/j.ophtha.2018.03.032. Epub 2018 Apr 25. PMID: 29705054. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29705054/","Atkins EJ, Bruce BB, Newman NJ, Biousse V. Treatment of nonarteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy. Surv Ophthalmol. 2010 Jan-Feb;55(1):47-63. doi: 10.1016/j.survophthal.2009.06.008. PMID: 20006051; PMCID: PMC3721361. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3721361/","Kim MK, Kim US. Analysis of Fundus Photography and Fluorescein Angiography in Nonarteritic Anterior Ischemic Optic Neuropathy and Optic Neuritis. Korean J Ophthalmol. 2016 Aug;30(4):289-94. doi: 10.3341/kjo.2016.30.4.289. Epub 2016 Jul 21. PMID: 27478356; PMCID: PMC4965604. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4965604/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63248"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63248"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T08:34:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T10:15:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5045"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77732"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"